<font color="#FF0000">WHY THE SILENCE?</font><br>
<tt>Mon Jul 28  0:46:49 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Why  is the term consciencous objector such a red flag for me? Probably for the same reason I see ex-drug crazed Vietnam Vet as a false portrayal of those I served with. <br>
I see RED probably because it was consciencous objectors that under the banner of religion provided food and medical supplies to the Communist soldiers we so often engaged in battle. We dug out tonsof  rice, and medical supplies, supplied by the Menonites and Quakers to the enemy in our area of responsibilty. That's why I see RED. <br><br>
WHY THE SILENCE?<br>
I can't really tell you why those I served with remained silent after the war, other then what I have already mentioned above. I can tell you for sure that it certainly was NOT FOR ANY OF THE REASONS YOU HAVE OUTLINED ABOVE. <br><br>
After Vietnam, I could not find others that I could share my feelings about the war.  I was proud of what we accomplished and many because of the negativeness reported in the media could not understand form of pride.<br><br>
Perhaps portions of the following three letters can help explain why we as a Marine unit remained silent. I believe they represent why other Vietnam veterans kept silent about their days of service, because they too served with pride and honor and were branded otherwise. <br><br>
From a machine gunner in 1st platoon;<br><br>
&quot;After I left, my memories laid mostly dormant for many years. Occasionally I would over hear a conversation that would cause me to think back and once in awhile I would have a fleeting thought of places and people that I served with, but mostly went on with my life. <br>
Like you, I hardly ever talked with anyone about Viet Nam to any degree because most did not understand the intensity of our feelings and could not fathom the underlying emotion that we all hadģ <br>
After all these years, we may not recall the places and events the same, but we do remember, and that is important. Looking at the photos that I have left, I see a bunch of kids, much like my own, who were not sure of what would become of them or why they did the things we did. But at the end of the day we had the certainty of each other and I believe we did quite well given the circumstances. If I had to do it over again I would want the same group of Marines at my side.<br>
Many in our country questioned and de-based our actions and the war that we fought but could not comprehend that freedom and liberty is non-selective, and resides only in those who fight for it, and then cherish it. <br>
The society that I see today is consumed with self-preference, greed and the desire to serve only the self. But buried in this society are the seeds of success for future generations, that being the children of all the servicemen who fought and died in Viet Nam and all other wars. These children have the traits of their fathers, passed on by us, and will certainly bloom and change our country. I have a deep respect for all living things and enjoy the little things in life<br>
As to your questions concerning battle events, places and other Marines we served with, I will take a little time to recall as best I can then write it down in some kind of order and send it to you. Some of my memories are very vivid, some dim but I hope they will be helpful to you. I should be finished in about a week. Writing a book is an enormous task and I await the publication with enthusiasm. It speaks well of you to chronicle our lives as they were and have the patience to tackle this project. Again, thanks for calling me. Now I know that my memories and experiences of Viet Nam are also yours and all the other Marines from our Company and we can share them together. Enclosed are some of the photos that I have left including a handsome young man named &quot;Cookie&quot;! I hope they help you. If I'm not out of the country, I will try to attend the next reunion. Till then, watch your backside and keep your helmet on!&quot;<br><br>
I had invited a Vietnam Veteran and psychologist friend of mine who works with veterans daily to join us during our 1st platoon reunion, which was held in February of this year. He was to be so to speak a fly on the wall. For three days, he saw us interact, he listened to and taped our reunion conversations. We held nothing back but shared our fears, joys and concerns. Afterwards the doctor wrote us all a letter, in which a portion said,<br>
&quot;In today's world, we and our children search for heroes whom we can emulate. We reach out to stars of various kinds, from music, to film, to sports. Yet, we feel unfulfilled in that quest because these people have not really done anything that would qualify them as heroes.<br>
I have spoken to audiences of upwards of a thousand people, without the difficulty I had in trying to say a few simple words to the men of 1st Platoon. I had the difficulty because of the honor which these men so richly deserve, based upon what they have done for freedom which all Americans, and citizens of many nations, have, and many take for granted. To be with this many men, who are truly heroes, was an awesome honor and experience.<br><br>
During the reunion this former Army Vietnam Veteran and Psychologist broke down when he tried to address us, why? Why the silence?<br><br>
Following the reunion. Our platoon lieutenant wrote us all a letter in it he said, <br><br>
&quot; Those who ridiculed or politicized what we did lost sight of the fact that we were doing what our country asked of us because we were true patriotic Americans, attempting to perform a task motivated by the belief we were to accomplish good and that is how we fought. In accomplishing our objectives, the men of the First platoon had a wonderfully unique ability to perform whatever task that was assigned, while showing such enormous care for one another. You men were quiet heroes, the type that don't seek nor usually receive recognition, but are those who deserve it most. We seemed to be satisfied that all of us supported each other and approved of what we did accomplished and the way it was accomplished.<br><br>
I believe many of us cherished that unity we felt in Vietnam, and could not share that with a world that despised and rejected those we knew that served our country with honor.  The world would not understand. <br>
I believe many of us have never taken the time to think through much of what transpired at that time.  As I have written, History's shame denied us the right to share those memories with our love ones. Perhaps the silence was because the same military service that brought us together was also responsible for annulling those common bonds. <br><br>
Of the 29 Marines I have found that served in 1st platoon (there were usually 47 of us a platoon), 12 of us were able to come together last February. Not one of us had spoken to another Marine in all that time, 30 years of silence. Why? Perhaps I have opened up more questions then what I have answered.<br>

<p><code>-- cookbarela@iname.com  (Cook Barela) </code><p>


